\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\f1\fs32\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs32\cgrid {Problem Statement
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {We want to build a teaching }{\b machine}{ to show students learning C++ the effect of }{\b code}{. The teaching machine is an abstraction of a }{\b computer}{ as seen from the unique point of view of a C++ }{\b compiler}{; it includes }{\b standard}{ }{\b resources}{, specifically a }{\b memory store}{ (divided up into }{\b static memory}{, a }{\b stack}{ and a }{\b heap}{) and an }{\b instruction counter }{(which references C++ }{\b instructions}{ not machine code); additionally, it has some }{\b special resources}{ such as an }{\b expression engine}{ (which can show the step by step evaluation of C++ }{\b expressions}{), a }{\b parser}{ (which breaks C++ code into }{\b tokens}{) and possibly a }{\b lexical analyzer}{. Resources are to be represented graphically to permit students to see the flow of }{\b data}{, the importance of }{\b types}{, and the mysteries of }{\b pointers }{& }{\b references}{.
\par The machine should recognize (ANSI) standard C++ files. It will NOT handle preprocessor directives, treating them as no-ops, nor will it handle any machine-specific extensions (e.g. far pointers). It will have only the most primitive}{\b  i/o facilities}{ (perhaps an }{\b output screen}{ linked to }{\b cout}{ and }{\b cin}{). It will have no linker (i.e. only one source file at a time).
\par It does not }{\i need}{ an error facility beyond the simple reporting of }{\i legal but unsupported C++ instruction}{. Source code }{\i may}{ be assumed to be well formed and to have compiled without error on a conventional ANSI compiler.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\f1\fs28\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\fi-720\li1440\sb120\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f1\fs28\cgrid {Discussion
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {It is worth emphasizing that the teaching machine is designed for teaching (that is for demonstration of the effects of code) and nothing else. In particular, it is not intended to be a simulator, a compiler or a debugger (although, in fact, it has attributes of all three).
\par The machine is predicated on the notion that beginning students are often not aware that every token of code has a specific effect. Many beginners exhibit superstitious behaviour. Bits and pieces of random code are inserted into programs in the belief that, because they worked before, in some other context, or for somebody else, they are somehow necessary. Like the eye of newt or wing of bat mixed in with healing herbs they are at best superfluous. Often they are downright dangerous. The teaching machine is intended to demonstrate directly that every piece of code has an effect.
\par A second effect will be to impose a consistent notation, particularly for memory display, that can be used elsewhere (i.e. course notes, or on the whiteboard).
\par By blending the abstractions necessary for the underlying machine (the standard resources) with those used by the compiler (special resources), it becomes easy to show that every statement has an effect. Even declarations (normally passed over by a debugger) will  change the state of the teaching machine. In this model, a declaration is treated as a request to the symbol table for an entry and to the particular memory store (static or stack) for an allocation.
\par It could be argued that, technically, the teaching machine is an interpreter. That is not a path I am interested in for two reasons. In the first instance, Term 3 students have enough on their plate without having to worry about the distinctions between a compiler and interpreter. More importantly, forcing the teaching machine onto pre-existing models will inevitably bend it out of the desired shape.
\par Finally, it is not important that the machine be able to explore all the darker corners of C++ and C.  It is not a compiler so reasonable restrictions on what it can handle are acceptable. What does matter is that it should be able to }{\i span}{ a good part of the code space that intermediate programming students can expect to encounter. It should be commented that it is for that reason that the #include directive has been explicitly added. Students may well want to run their own code through the machine and this will inevitably have includes in it for standard library declarations. Few darker corners in C exist than in these. The idea is not that the machine will actually include these files. Rather it will note them and pass them discreetly by.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\f1\fs32\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs32\cgrid {System Charter Statement
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {The Teaching Machine, Release 2, will be able to
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls2\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {Accept as input simple, short ( <150 instructions) ANSI C++ files prepared on a standard C++ editor. Only a subset of C++ syntax would be implemented (see list below). Syntax }{\i may be}{ assumed to have been validated already by a regular compiler as part of the editing process.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls3\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls3\adjustright {Check the source code for syntax errors (extra rules only).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 3.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls4\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls4\adjustright {Step through the source code, }{\i expression by expression.}{ Also back up in the source code. (If it helps simplify the stepping process instructions }{\i may be}{ constrained to be line oriented (i.e. one ';' per line). In the event that assumption is made it is not }{\i necessary}{ to check the source for conformance).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 4.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls5\adjustright {Show the effect of the source code on the symbol table, the instruction counter, the stack, the static memory store, the heap, the expression engine and the output screen.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 5.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls6\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls6\adjustright {Be able to step through and back up within a single expression (already implemented in Release 1).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 6.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls7\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls7\adjustright {Be capable of being restarted, of stepping over or into functions,  or advancing to a designated line.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 7.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls8\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls8\adjustright {Be graceful in its rejection of unsupported (but normally legal) code. The machine should ignore it and go forward as best it can. It may quit if it has to (but it should not crash).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s16 \f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 8.\tab}}\pard \s16\qj\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls9\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent720\pnhang{\pntxta .}}\ls9\adjustright {All memory objects should be able to display themselves using the standard format developed in Release 1, or, as raw bytes. Compound memory objects should display both as single entities or be expanded into their component entities.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\f1\fs28\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\fi-720\li1440\sb120\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f1\fs28\cgrid {C++ Subset
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.1.1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\fi-720\li2160\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright \b\f1\fs22\cgrid {Reserved Words
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {break, case, char, const, continue, delete, do, double, else, enum, for, if, int, long, new, return, static, struct, switch,  unsigned, void, while
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.1.2.\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\fi-720\li2160\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright \b\f1\fs22\cgrid {Types
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {Bool, char, int, long, double, unsigned, pointer to all of these, array of all of them
\par Enum (no over-rides)
\par Structure (simple only, no embedding of }{\i any }{compound types)
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs22\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.1.3.\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\fi-720\li2160\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright \b\f1\fs22\cgrid {Operators
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {\b [ ]}{  }{\b ( )}{  }{{\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 183 \\f "Symbol" \\s 11}{\fldrslt\f3\fs22}}}{  }{\b ->}{  }{\b ++}{   }{\b --}{   }{\b &}{   }{\b *   +   -   ~   !   /   %   <<   >>   <   >   <=   >=   ==  !=  ^  |  ||  &&   ? :   =  *=  /=  %=  +=  -=  &=  ^=  |=   }{
\par Note that the ++ and - - operators should be implemented in both post and pre forms and the << and >> are only needed in their overloaded sense as insertion and extraction operators for streams. The bitwise logical operators would be a lower priority than the rest.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\f1\fs28\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2.2.\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\fi-720\li1440\sb120\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f1\fs28\cgrid {Discussion
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {It will be noted that virtually none of the features that put the ++ into C++ are implemented, notably classes and everything that derives from them. One must start somewhere. Adding classes would add substantially to the project's complexity, Moreover, students wrestle most with the notion of the underlying machine at the beginning of the term, before classes are introduced.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\f1\fs32\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 3.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs32\cgrid {Graphics
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {It is proposed that a modified version of the Graphics used in Release 1 be employed. The modification will consist of the Graphic code being stripped out of the existing classes and implemented as a separate graphics interface package. This will be done by the client and a new interface defined.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\f1\fs32\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 4.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs32\cgrid {Implementation Language
\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs22\cgrid {The teaching machine is intended to be used both as a demonstrator in lectures as well as a tutorial device for students to use. Ideally it would be usable both over the world wide web as well as distributable to students for use on their own home machines. At the moment, those two goals are not always easily reconciled since Windows uses a file metaphor while the web uses web addresses. Nevertheless, it is expected that issue will be resolved in the fairly near future. (It is resolvable now if students actually host their own web on their own machine as FrontPage permits. However this requires an investment on their part in a piece of software many of them would not otherwise need, a less than ideal circumstance.)
\par }\pard \qj\fi576\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {The upshot is that the teaching machine is to be implemented in Java, ideally as an applet (or set of applets) so that it can be invoked from a browser. This version }{\i may}{ be implemented as a standalone Java application so long as the code that prevents it from being an applet (e.g. manipulating the filing system) is isolated and encapsulated for easy replacement.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\f1\fs32\cgrid \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 5.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\fi-720\li720\sb240\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\ls1\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f1\fs32\cgrid {Release 1
